and also really likes pink.

00:53.637 --> 00:54.845
[laughs]

00:54.889 --> 00:56.513
<i>- My name's Eric Anthony Leong.</i>

00:56.557 --> 00:59.516
<i> I'm part bladesmith,</i>
<i> part prop fabricator, part DJ.</i>

00:59.560 --> 01:02.519
<i> I'm half Chinese.</i>
<i> I love going back to my roots,</i>

01:02.563 --> 01:05.397
and I get my inspiration
from my family.

01:05.441 --> 01:07.399
<i> - My name is Jared Williams.</i>

01:07.443 --> 01:09.568
I've been making knives
for 27 years.

01:09.612 --> 01:12.321
I get sanity from
the knife-making process.

01:12.364 --> 01:15.032
<i> It's like this whole</i>
<i> body-mind-spirit.</i>

01:15.076 --> 01:16.909
<i> I don't want to make knives.</i>

01:16.952 --> 01:20.662
I have to make knives.

01:20.706 --> 01:23.540
- Bladesmiths,
welcome to the Forge.

01:23.584 --> 01:25.459
You have volunteered to engage

01:25.503 --> 01:27.669
in three rounds of edged
weapon-making competition,

01:27.713 --> 01:30.756
designed to test every aspect
of your capabilities,

01:30.800 --> 01:33.634
from design to forge
to fit and finish.

01:33.677 --> 01:35.928
At the end of each round,
you will present your work

01:35.971 --> 01:38.180
to our panel of expert judges.

01:38.224 --> 01:41.725
First up, master bladesmith
Jason Knight,

01:41.769 --> 01:45.938
historic weapons re-creation
specialist David Baker,

01:45.981 --> 01:49.650
and last, edged weapons
specialist, Doug Marcaida.

01:49.693 --> 01:51.485
Ultimately, they decide
which of you

01:51.529 --> 01:53.529
will be the "Forged in Fire"
champion

01:53.572 --> 01:56.698
who also leaves here
with a check for $10,000.

01:56.742 --> 01:58.408
In your first round
of competition,

01:58.452 --> 02:00.577
you'll be using this.

02:00.621 --> 02:07.417
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

02:07.461 --> 02:09.336
<i> - I am completely confused.</i>

02:09.380 --> 02:11.004
There's nothing there.

02:11.048 --> 02:14.591
- Don't worry, guys.
We didn't forget your steel.

02:14.635 --> 02:17.136
All of the tools that you need
to make your blades

02:17.179 --> 02:19.471
are on the tool
stands next to you,

02:19.515 --> 02:22.015
including your steel.

02:22.059 --> 02:23.392
In your first round challenge,

02:23.435 --> 02:24.768
you'll have to pick
from the tools

02:24.812 --> 02:26.520
on the table in front of you
to forge

02:26.564 --> 02:29.773
a signature blade
of your own design.

02:29.817 --> 02:32.651
Choose wisely
because there's plenty of steel,

02:32.695 --> 02:35.154
but only a limited
number of tools.

02:35.197 --> 02:36.405
<i>- I'm looking over at the cart.</i>

02:36.448 --> 02:38.031
<i> I'm seeing hammers,</i>

02:38.075 --> 02:39.908
and I was like,
"I might really need those."

02:39.952 --> 02:42.161
So I was kind of reluctant
to have to build out of that.

02:42.204 --> 02:43.453
- The blades themselves
must fall

02:43.497 --> 02:45.080
within the following parameters:

02:45.124 --> 02:47.457
<i> the length of the blade,</i>
<i> not including the tang,</i>

02:47.501 --> 02:50.169
<i> must be between</i>
<i> 11 and 16 inches.</i>

02:50.212 --> 02:51.962
<i> The overall length</i>
<i> of your weapon</i>

02:52.006 --> 02:54.464
must not exceed 22 inches.

02:54.508 --> 02:55.966
Keep in mind that
in the second round,

02:56.010 --> 02:57.467
you'll be attaching handles
to your blades

02:57.511 --> 02:59.678
to turn them into
fully functional weapons

02:59.722 --> 03:01.972
that will then be tested
for strength and durability

03:02.016 --> 03:06.768
in an ice chop and for sharpness
in a tatami mat slice.

03:06.812 --> 03:09.062
And just to keep things
a little bit more interesting,

03:09.106 --> 03:12.983
you must also include
a serrated edge in your blades.

03:13.027 --> 03:14.943
You will have ten minutes
to work on your design.

03:14.987 --> 03:17.654
You will have three hours
to forge your blades.

03:17.698 --> 03:20.657
When the time runs out,
one of you will be asked

03:20.701 --> 03:23.744
to surrender his weapon
and leave the Forge.

03:23.787 --> 03:25.037
Good luck.

03:25.080 --> 03:28.081
Your time starts now.

03:28.125 --> 03:30.542
These guys have got a lot
of tools to choose from.

03:30.586 --> 03:33.086
They've got hammers.
They've got fullering tools.

03:33.130 --> 03:34.713
They've got files.

03:34.757 --> 03:37.299
Over here, Ryan has
pulled out some files.

03:37.343 --> 03:39.343
- Yeah.
The files are a good idea, Dave.

03:39.386 --> 03:41.220
- Well, yeah.
They've got so many of them.

03:41.263 --> 03:43.222
I mean, even if they use one,
they'll still have more files

03:43.265 --> 03:45.682
to do whatever finish work
they need to do with a file.

03:45.726 --> 03:47.684
<i> - I was kind of looking</i>
<i> at the steels I have to use,</i>

03:47.728 --> 03:48.977
<i> and I was just kind of like,</i>

03:49.021 --> 03:51.855
<i> "Ugh."</i>

03:51.899 --> 03:54.441
I'm gonna be building a blade
that's a competition chopper.

03:54.485 --> 03:56.318
The big part is serrations,

03:56.362 --> 03:58.695
<i> where that edge is really</i>
<i> gonna meet that tatami mat.</i>

03:58.739 --> 04:00.697
<i>So I want to get the serrations</i>
<i> as fine as possible</i>

04:00.741 --> 04:04.576
<i> so that they're not grabbing</i>
<i> and tearing material.</i>

04:04.620 --> 04:06.161
<i> I was trying to figure out,</i>
<i> "Do I use the hammer?</i>

04:06.205 --> 04:08.121
Is a file big enough?
No."

04:08.165 --> 04:12.501
<i>I'm going with kind of a hybrid</i>
<i> tanto-kukri kind of thing,</i>

04:12.544 --> 04:14.211
<i> and then, I'm hoping to keep</i>

04:14.255 --> 04:16.588
<i> the serrates kind of</i>
<i> near the base of the blade.</i>

04:18.425 --> 04:20.717
I'm drawing something
that feels sexy--

04:20.761 --> 04:22.594
that's gonna look good
with big serrations.

04:22.638 --> 04:24.179
<i> I have picked this design</i>

04:24.223 --> 04:25.514
<i> because I think that</i>
<i> it'll swing well,</i>

04:25.557 --> 04:27.557
<i> and they're gonna be chopping.</i>

04:27.601 --> 04:29.101
<i> - I chose a hammer</i>
<i> because I know</i>

04:29.144 --> 04:32.229
<i> that I actually have enough</i>
<i> other hammers</i>

04:32.273 --> 04:34.231
to get the job done.

04:34.275 --> 04:36.149
<i> I'm designing Chinese dadao.</i>

04:36.193 --> 04:40.737
It's designed for cutting
down brush and also execution.

04:40.781 --> 04:43.073
<i> It's gonna be</i>
<i> a significant chopper.</i>

04:43.117 --> 04:45.826
I'm also putting
a serrated edge on the back.

04:45.869 --> 04:47.494
<i> I want to make it</i>
<i> look apocalyptic.</i>

04:47.538 --> 04:50.622
- Three, two, one.

04:50.666 --> 04:52.749
Bladesmiths, your design window
has closed.

04:52.793 --> 04:56.128
Your three-hour
forging time starts now.

04:56.171 --> 04:58.380
<i> [heavy metal music]</i>

04:58.424 --> 04:59.923
So we're off.

04:59.967 --> 05:05.178
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

05:05.222 --> 05:08.807
So Harlan and Ryan cleaning
teeth off of their files,

05:08.851 --> 05:10.976
and then, over here,
we've got Jared

05:11.020 --> 05:13.478
and Eric working with hammers.

05:13.522 --> 05:15.772
<i> [dramatic music]</i>

05:15.816 --> 05:19.484
- I go straight to the grinder
to remove the teeth.

05:19.528 --> 05:20.777
Welding.

